## Description {#details}

This file contains some templates that are useful if you are working with the STL at all.

No library is required when using these functions.

<Link id="l00428" /><CodeLine lineNumber="428"><Highlight kind="comment">/// An iterator adaptor that filters the elements of given inner iterators.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00429" /><CodeLine lineNumber="429"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00430" /><CodeLine lineNumber="430"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The predicate parameter should be a callable object that accepts the wrapped</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00431" /><CodeLine lineNumber="431"><Highlight kind="comment">/// iterator&#39;s reference type and returns a bool. When incrementing or</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00432" /><CodeLine lineNumber="432"><Highlight kind="comment">/// decrementing the iterator, it will call the predicate on each element and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00433" /><CodeLine lineNumber="433"><Highlight kind="comment">/// skip any where it returns false.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00434" /><CodeLine lineNumber="434"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00435" /><CodeLine lineNumber="435"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\code</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00436" /><CodeLine lineNumber="436"><Highlight kind="comment">///   int A&#91;&#93; = &#123; 1, 2, 3, 4 &#125;;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00437" /><CodeLine lineNumber="437"><Highlight kind="comment">///   auto R = make&#95;filter&#95;range(A, &#91;&#93;(int N) &#123; return N % 2 == 1; &#125;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00438" /><CodeLine lineNumber="438"><Highlight kind="comment">///   // R contains &#123; 1, 3 &#125;.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00439" /><CodeLine lineNumber="439"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\endcode</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00440" /><CodeLine lineNumber="440"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00441" /><CodeLine lineNumber="441"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Note: filter&#95;iterator&#95;base implements support for forward iteration.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00442" /><CodeLine lineNumber="442"><Highlight kind="comment">/// filter&#95;iterator&#95;impl exists to provide support for bidirectional iteration,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00443" /><CodeLine lineNumber="443"><Highlight kind="comment">/// conditional on whether the wrapped iterator supports it.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00583" /><CodeLine lineNumber="583"><Highlight kind="comment">/// A pseudo-iterator adaptor that is designed to implement &quot;early increment&quot;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00584" /><CodeLine lineNumber="584"><Highlight kind="comment">/// style loops.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00585" /><CodeLine lineNumber="585"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00586" /><CodeLine lineNumber="586"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This is &#42;not a normal iterator&#42; and should almost never be used directly. It</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00587" /><CodeLine lineNumber="587"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is intended primarily to be used with range based for loops and some range</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00588" /><CodeLine lineNumber="588"><Highlight kind="comment">/// algorithms.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00589" /><CodeLine lineNumber="589"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00590" /><CodeLine lineNumber="590"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The iterator isn&#39;t quite an &#96;OutputIterator&#96; or an &#96;InputIterator&#96; but</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00591" /><CodeLine lineNumber="591"><Highlight kind="comment">/// somewhere between them. The constraints of these iterators are:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00592" /><CodeLine lineNumber="592"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00593" /><CodeLine lineNumber="593"><Highlight kind="comment">/// - On construction or after being incremented, it is comparable and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00594" /><CodeLine lineNumber="594"><Highlight kind="comment">///   dereferencable. It is &#42;not&#42; incrementable.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00595" /><CodeLine lineNumber="595"><Highlight kind="comment">/// - After being dereferenced, it is neither comparable nor dereferencable, it</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00596" /><CodeLine lineNumber="596"><Highlight kind="comment">///   is only incrementable.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00597" /><CodeLine lineNumber="597"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00598" /><CodeLine lineNumber="598"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This means you can only dereference the iterator once, and you can only</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00599" /><CodeLine lineNumber="599"><Highlight kind="comment">/// increment it once between dereferences.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00600" /><CodeLine lineNumber="600"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> WrappedIteratorT&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00643" /><CodeLine lineNumber="643"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Make a range that does early increment to allow mutation of the underlying</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00644" /><CodeLine lineNumber="644"><Highlight kind="comment">/// range without disrupting iteration.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00645" /><CodeLine lineNumber="645"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00646" /><CodeLine lineNumber="646"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The underlying iterator will be incremented immediately after it is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00647" /><CodeLine lineNumber="647"><Highlight kind="comment">/// dereferenced, allowing deletion of the current node or insertion of nodes to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00648" /><CodeLine lineNumber="648"><Highlight kind="comment">/// not disrupt iteration provided they do not invalidate the &#42;next&#42; iterator --</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00649" /><CodeLine lineNumber="649"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the current iterator can be invalidated.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00650" /><CodeLine lineNumber="650"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00651" /><CodeLine lineNumber="651"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This requires a very exact pattern of use that is only really suitable to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00652" /><CodeLine lineNumber="652"><Highlight kind="comment">/// range based for loops and other range algorithms that explicitly guarantee</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00653" /><CodeLine lineNumber="653"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to dereference exactly once each element, and to increment exactly once each</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00654" /><CodeLine lineNumber="654"><Highlight kind="comment">/// element.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00655" /><CodeLine lineNumber="655"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> RangeT&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00657" /><CodeLine lineNumber="657" lineLink="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#a3d2cdc4a0db233678e7141c9d6ea3419"><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#a3d2cdc4a0db233678e7141c9d6ea3419">make&#95;early&#95;inc&#95;range</a>(RangeT &amp;&amp;<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/nvptx/nvvmintrrange-cpp/#a34bd74317e3f04bfc4318c2d1a470877">Range</a>) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1011"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Iterator wrapper that concatenates sequences together.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1012"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1013"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This can concatenate different iterators, even with different types, into</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1014"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a single iterator provided the value types of all the concatenated</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1015"><Highlight kind="comment">/// iterators expose &#96;reference&#96; and &#96;pointer&#96; types that can be converted to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1016"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#96;ValueT &amp;&#96; and &#96;ValueT &#42;&#96; respectively. It doesn&#39;t support more</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01017" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1017"><Highlight kind="comment">/// interesting/customized pointer or reference types.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01018" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1018"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01019" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1019"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Currently this only supports forward or higher iterator categories as</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01020" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1020"><Highlight kind="comment">/// inputs and always exposes a forward iterator interface.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01021" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1021"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> ValueT, </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">... IterTs&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1037"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// We store both the current and end iterators for each concatenated</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1038"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// sequence in a tuple of pairs.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1039"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1040"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Note that something like iterator&#95;range seems nice at first here, but the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1041"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// range properties are of little benefit and end up getting in the way</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1042"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// because we need to do mutation on the current iterators.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1046"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Attempts to increment a specific iterator.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1047"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1048"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Returns true if it was able to increment the iterator. Returns false if</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1049"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// the iterator is already at the end iterator.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1050"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">size&#95;t</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> Index&gt; </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">bool</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> incrementHelper() &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01060" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1060"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Increments the first non-end iterator.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01061" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1061"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1062"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// It is an error to call this with all iterators at the end.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1063"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">size&#95;t</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">... <Link id="l01064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1064"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Build a sequence of functions to increment each iterator if possible.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1065"><Highlight kind="normal">    bool (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/concat-iterator/#ac566cb13277fd8d2b3423537cbe733ef">concat&#95;iterator</a>::&#42;IncrementHelperFns&#91;&#93;)() = &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1066"><Highlight kind="normal">        &amp;concat&#95;iterator::incrementHelper&lt;Ns&gt;...&#125;;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1068"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Loop over them, and stop as soon as we succeed at incrementing one.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01069" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1069"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">for</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">auto</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &amp;IncrementHelperFn : IncrementHelperFns)</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01517" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1517"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01518" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1518"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Returns an opaquely-typed Callable object whose operator() overload set is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01519" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1519"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the sum of the operator() overload sets of each CallableT in CallableTs.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01520" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1520"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01521" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1521"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The type of the returned object derives from each CallableT in CallableTs.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01522" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1522"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The returned object is constructed by invoking the appropriate copy or move</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01523" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1523"><Highlight kind="comment">/// constructor of each CallableT, as selected by overload resolution on the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01524" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1524"><Highlight kind="comment">/// corresponding argument to makeVisitor.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01525" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1525"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01526" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1526"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Example:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01527" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1527"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01528" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1528"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\code</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01529" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1529"><Highlight kind="comment">/// auto visitor = makeVisitor(&#91;&#93;(auto) &#123; return &quot;unhandled type&quot;; &#125;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01530" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1530"><Highlight kind="comment">///                            &#91;&#93;(int i) &#123; return &quot;int&quot;; &#125;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01531" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1531"><Highlight kind="comment">///                            &#91;&#93;(std::string s) &#123; return &quot;str&quot;; &#125;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01532" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1532"><Highlight kind="comment">/// auto a = visitor(42);    // &#96;a&#96; is now &quot;int&quot;.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01533" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1533"><Highlight kind="comment">/// auto b = visitor(&quot;foo&quot;); // &#96;b&#96; is now &quot;str&quot;.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01534" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1534"><Highlight kind="comment">/// auto c = visitor(3.14f); // &#96;c&#96; is now &quot;unhandled type&quot;.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01535" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1535"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\endcode</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01536" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1536"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01537" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1537"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Example of making a visitor with a lambda which captures a move-only type:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01538" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1538"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01539" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1539"><Highlight kind="comment">/// \\code</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01540" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1540"><Highlight kind="comment">/// std::unique&#95;ptr&lt;FooHandler&gt; FH = /&#42; ... &#42;/;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01541" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1541"><Highlight kind="comment">/// auto visitor = makeVisitor(</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01542" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1542"><Highlight kind="comment">///     &#91;FH&#123;std::move(FH)&#125;&#93;(Foo F) &#123; return FH-&gt;handle(F); &#125;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01543" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1543"><Highlight kind="comment">///     &#91;&#93;(int i) &#123; return i; &#125;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01544" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1544"><Highlight kind="comment">///     &#91;&#93;(std::string s) &#123; return atoi(s); &#125;);</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01609" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1609"><Highlight kind="comment">/// array&#95;pod&#95;sort - This sorts an array with the specified start and end</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01610" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1610"><Highlight kind="comment">/// extent.  This is just like std::sort, except that it calls qsort instead of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01611" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1611"><Highlight kind="comment">/// using an inlined template.  qsort is slightly slower than std::sort, but</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01612" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1612"><Highlight kind="comment">/// most sorts are not performance critical in LLVM and std::sort has to be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01613" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1613"><Highlight kind="comment">/// template instantiated for each type, leading to significant measured code</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01614" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1614"><Highlight kind="comment">/// bloat.  This function should generally be used instead of std::sort where</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01615" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1615"><Highlight kind="comment">/// possible.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01616" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1616"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01617" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1617"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This function assumes that you have simple POD-like types that can be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01618" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1618"><Highlight kind="comment">/// compared with std::less and can be moved with memcpy.  If this isn&#39;t true,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01619" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1619"><Highlight kind="comment">/// you should use std::sort.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01620" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1620"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01621" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1621"><Highlight kind="comment">/// NOTE: If qsort&#95;r were portable, we could allow a custom comparator and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01622" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1622"><Highlight kind="comment">/// default to std::less.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01623" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1623"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">&lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> IteratorTy&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l02411" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2411"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Given two or more input ranges, returns a new range whose values are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02412" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2412"><Highlight kind="comment">/// tuples (A, B, C, ...), such that A is the 0-based index of the item in the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02413" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2413"><Highlight kind="comment">/// sequence, and B, C, ..., are the values from the original input ranges. All</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02414" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2414"><Highlight kind="comment">/// input ranges are required to have equal lengths. Note that the returned</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02415" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2415"><Highlight kind="comment">/// iterator allows for the values (B, C, ...) to be modified.  Example:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02416" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2416"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02417" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2417"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#96;&#96;&#96;c++</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02418" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2418"><Highlight kind="comment">/// std::vector&lt;char&gt; Letters = &#123;&#39;A&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;C&#39;, &#39;D&#39;&#125;;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02419" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2419"><Highlight kind="comment">/// std::vector&lt;int&gt; Vals = &#123;10, 11, 12, 13&#125;;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02420" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2420"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02421" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2421"><Highlight kind="comment">/// for (auto &#91;Index, Letter, Value&#93; : enumerate(Letters, Vals)) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02422" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2422"><Highlight kind="comment">///   printf(&quot;Item %zu - %c: %d\\n&quot;, Index, Letter, Value);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02423" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2423"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Value -= 10;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02424" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2424"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02425" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2425"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#96;&#96;&#96;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02426" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2426"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02427" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2427"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Output:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02428" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2428"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Item 0 - A: 10</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02429" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2429"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Item 1 - B: 11</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02430" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2430"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Item 2 - C: 12</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02431" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2431"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Item 3 - D: 13</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02432" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2432"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02433" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2433"><Highlight kind="comment">/// or using an iterator:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02434" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2434"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &#96;&#96;&#96;c++</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l02435" /><CodeLine lineNumber="2435"><Highlight kind="comment">/// for (auto it : enumerate(Vals)) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
